{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17524647","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17524647"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:06:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:06:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14017"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14017","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14017"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.04,0.01,0.32,0.5]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6666"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54925"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6666","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6666"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14017"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40443"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"2422"},{"type":"tags","id":"4663"},{"type":"tags","id":"4772"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4970"},{"type":"tags","id":"6408"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13695"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37117"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54925","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/54925"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 50-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-month history of increasing difficulty with micturition. While he still has a good stream, once micturition starts, it sprays in all directions. He does not have any nocturia or dysuria. He has had several new sexual encounters over the last year, including a visit to a brothel. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The only abnormal finding is apparent when he is asked to retract his foreskin as much as he can (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Syphilis","Genital herpes","Contact dermatitis","Candida balanitis","Lichen sclerosus"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation and examination findings in this case are most consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Elichen sclerosus\u003C/strong\u003E of the penis, formerly known as balanitis xerotica obliterans. There are whitish, atrophic patches visible on the glans penis and inner surface of the foreskin. The foreskin appears tight and cannot be fully retracted. This chronic inflammatory condition typically presents with whitish, atrophic patches on the glans penis and foreskin, as seen in the image. Chronic irritation and trauma are important aetiological factors in the development of lichen sclerosis, but often the cause is unknown. The development of phimosis, where there is a tight foreskin that cannot be fully retracted, is a common complication, which explains this patient\u0027s spraying of urine during micturition. Lichen sclerosus can also lead to urethral stricture if left untreated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESyphilis\u003C/strong\u003E can cause genital lesions, but these typically present as painless, firm, round, and small chancres in the primary stage, or as a diffuse rash in the secondary stage. The chronic, atrophic changes seen in this case are not characteristic of syphilis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGenital herpes\u003C/strong\u003E presents with painful vesicles or ulcers on the genitals, which rupture and heal over time. It does not cause the chronic, atrophic changes or phimosis seen in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContact dermatitis\u003C/strong\u003E of the penis would typically present with erythema, itching, and possibly vesicles or scaling. It would not cause the whitish, atrophic changes or phimosis seen in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECandida balanitis\u003C/strong\u003E usually presents with erythema, itching, and white patches on the glans penis and inner foreskin. However, these patches are typically removable (revealing an erythematous base) and are associated with a cottage cheese-like discharge, which are not described in this case. Candida infection also does not typically lead to phimosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management of penile lichen sclerosus typically involves potent topical corticosteroids and careful monitoring for complications such as urethral stricture. In cases of severe phimosis, circumcision may be necessary. It is important to note that while the patient\u0027s history of multiple sexual partners and visit to a brothel might raise suspicion for sexually transmitted infections, lichen sclerosus is not considered a sexually transmitted condition.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Lichen sclerosus of the penis (formerly known as balanitis xerotica obliterans) can cause phimosis and spraying of urine.","Lichen sclerosus typically presents with whitish, atrophic patches on the glans penis and foreskin.","Lichen sclerosus is a chronic inflammatory condition that can lead to urethral stricture if left untreated."],"references":["De Luca DA, Papara C, Vorobyev A, et al. Lichen sclerosus: The 2023 update.  Front Med (Lausanne). 2023 Feb 16:10:1106318.  doi: 10.3389/fmed.2023.1106318. eCollection 2023."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40443"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14017"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20928"}]},"explanationMedia":{